<br>
I am overwhelmed with the volume of support that we have received so far in countering this threat.  I am convinced that Gnoll mothers will use tales of this day to frighten their pups into obedience.<br>
<br>
My heart swells with pride.<br>
<br>
Also, I want to thank each and every one of you for not pointing out that I am a dolt and it is - in actuality - an *INTER* Guild event.<br>
<br>
Uinin Stormsong<br>
NOW with multiple languages! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=20371A><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uuininstormsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uinin Stormsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#660000>(4/13/02 4:43:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fcircleofsistersfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=357.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Retribution</span><hr size=1> The clouds continued to gather ominously on the horizon, sending forked tongues of lighting crashing to the Plains in the distance.  The wind picked up suddenly, sending swirling dervishes of dust dancing through the camp, snapping the banners straight.  The air was charged with electricity, both from the coming storm and from the assembled warriors around the spires.<br>
<br>
Uinin squatted atop the hilltop, staring into the heart of the coming storm.  Karana apparently gave his blessing to the raid, he thought with a sardonic laugh.  Or perhaps the coming squall was a manifestation of his displeasure.  Sometimes, it was hard to tell the difference.<br>
<br>
The camp arrayed at the foot of the hill was an impressive sight.  A small army mingled below, each preparing for the afternoon’s fight in their own way.  The Vah Shir contingent was a collective exposed nerve, ready to pounce on the hated enemies of their ancestors.  Tails twitching, the most composed of the Chosen of Vah still flexed their claws unconsciously, glaring at the direction of the Splitpaw stronghold in the South.<br>
<br>
A collection of others clustered in groups throughout the camps.  An enclave of Gnomes tinkered together a clockwork automaton by the cook fires, a whirling man-shaped toy that emitted ominous showers of blue sparks.  Sharp, twirling coils of twisted springs stuck from the joints, threatening to take the eye of anyone who inspected the jerkily dancing doll.<br>
<br>
A group of Rangers from the Ledenyetz Troupe met with their friends from the Circle of Sisters, sharing tales of reckless bravery and showing each other their battle scars.  Nearby, a cadre of Druids shook their heads sagely at the Rangers, chuckling softly as they fed bread crumbs to the chipmunks crowding around them.<br>
<br>
Dwarven fighters monopolized the brew kegs, swinging their tankards in the air and singing ribald fighting songs that brought color to the cheeks of more than one High Elf standing within earshot.<br>
<br>
The first drops of rain began falling amidst the camp as the storm rumbled nearer and nearer.  Uinin straightened, letting the rising wind snap his cloak straight behind him.  He patted his hip pouch absently, checking to see if his spare lute strings were safely wrapped in waxed canvas to protect them from the wet weather.  This day would generate a new body of work – new tales of bravery and songs of sacrifice.<br>
<br>
A thunderous boom sounded from near the mess tent, a thing pillar of blue smoke mushrooming above the camp.  A handful of Gnomes filtered into crowd, whistling innocently with their hands in their pockets, despite their soot-black faces.  <br>
<br>
Tereila sidled up to Uinin, one eye on a sooty Gnome who had started to piece together an eyeball-shaped globe, ringed with swirling blades.<br>
<br>
“All is ready, my friend,” she said, a grim smile touching her lips.  “With any luck, we will be upon them before the gnolls are aware of what has hit them.  All we await now is your command.”<br>
<br>
Tereila held out a gilded horn to the bard, the ceremonial Call to Arms.  Uinin took the instrument from her hesitantly, holding it as if it were a viper that might turn and strike him at any moment.  Glancing down at the camp, Uinin realized that every face was turned to him, every warrior awaiting his word to march to death.<br>
<br>
They would ask no quarter from their foe, and they would expect none in return.  There was no telling how many of the assembled heroes would return, how many would suffer, how many would die.  These fighters would deal death and destruction on his signal, and were willing to risk their lives to do.  Uinin swelled with pride.  They would march, and they would win.<br>
<br>
He lifted the horn to his lips and blew. A clear, strong clarion call carried over the Plains of Karana, signaling the start to the raid.  A rumbling roar rolled over the camp, and the Storm above answered in kind.<br>
<br>
++++++<br>
<br>
The Raid is upon us!<br>
<br>
We meet Sunday, April 14th to take the Gnoll’s cowardly war on the League of Antonican Bards to their vile homes.  <br>
<br>
We will assemble at the Spires in the Northern Plains of Karana at 11 a.m. ET for the initial briefing.  There we will split into groups that will proceed to the gnoll camps appropriate for their level.  There are four primary targets that can accommodate adventurers of almost any level.<br>
<br>
Blackburrow – The easiest of the dungeons, it is located in the Qeynos hills.  Soulbinders are available in Qeynos and (I think) in Surefall Glade.<br>
<br>
East Karana – On the Northern edge of the Eastern Plains is a hill that is infested with gnoll reavers.  Groups in their high teens should find these to be risky, but worth a try.  Binds are available Rivervale and the Highpass Hold (if you can find someone to bind you).<br>
<br>
Lake Rathetear – Low to mid-20s groups can make good coin in this zone.  To get to the camp, head to the southernmost edge of the Southern Plains of Karana.  The gnoll camp is right across the zone line.  I mean it… RIGHT across the zone line.  Binds are up to you.  The Gypsy camp in Northern Karana may be your best bet, unless it is possible to bind at the centaur or aviak cities.  <br>
<br>
Splitpaw – For the older adventurers, Splitpaw is a hive of loot, experience, and sudden and violent death.  I can offer no advice to anybody who wishes to go her other than to watch your back.<br>
<br>
If you want to join in, please jump in on the raid chat channel.  Simply type:<br>
<br>
/join gnollraid<br>
<br>
This is the general gnoll raid chat line.  The names in parentheses above indicate the camp specific channels.  Please try to use /say /gsay and /guildsay as often as possible for RP purposes.  Chat channels are meant for coordination between groups.<br>
<br>
If you have any questions, you can reach me in any number of ways.<br>
<br>
Web – <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.byteoart.com/ledenyetz">www.byteoart.com/ledenyetz</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> is the Ledenyetz Troupe’s home on the web, including message boards.<br>
<br>
E-Mail – send me a note at uinin2000@yahoo.com.  I’ll be happy to offer whatever aid I can.<br>
<br>
AIM – Instant Messenger users can send me an insta-note.  My AIM name is Uinin (go figure).  I’ve got AIM running all the time, and can easily check it while I’m in Norrath.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=20371A><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uuininstormsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uinin Stormsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#660000>(4/16/02 12:13:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fcircleofsistersfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=357.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Retribution</span><hr size=1> As the dust settles on the Plains of Karana, the combatants took stock of their accomplishments. <br>
<br>
The gnolls camped by the edge of the Rathetear were driven from their encampment, forced to flee ignobly into the murky waters of the lake.  Only now were the shattered remnants of their party slinking back to their clustered hovels.  Gnoll embalmers hurriedly dragged the mounds of corpses to the side, preparing dark magicks of untold horror.<br>
<br>
In Blackburrow, gnoll matrons kept young pups in line with hushed tales of Cronandan the Destroyer, the Scourge of Blackburrow.  Straighten up and obey the elders, they whispered, or the blue-skinned Angel of Death would again drown the stronghold in blood.<br>
<br>
In Splitpaw, Tesch'Val gnolls wandered in a state of shock.  Eyes rolling in terror at the sound of a single footfall, the spiritless curs rolled over instantly.  Gibbering about giant cats and the mighty hammers of the knee-high clerics, the Split Ear Tribe was driven to its knees in fear and shame.<br>
<br>
Across Norrath, the results were immediate.  Freed from the incursions of the vile gnolls, the League of Antonican Bards were once again free to onnect the world's peoples.  They carry words that must go through, yet again, setting Norrath's wheels of politics, intrigue, and comerce in motion once again.<br>
<br>
Thanks to all you attended the raid, it was a great blast as far as I was concerned, and i can't wait to do something like it again.  <br>
<br>
Before we go... I have a couple of awards I wish to bestow.  If you have any others you feel need to be acknowledged, please feel free to post your own.<br>
<br>
The &quot;Against all Odds&quot; Award goes to  - Razael of the Ledenyetz Troupe.  Despite being unable to group with anybody in Blackburrow, this young wood elf bravely traded blows with swarms of gnolls in the stronghold.  Way to get stuck in!<br>
<br>
The &quot;Rand McNally&quot; Award goes to - Purrcy Si'Rona of the Chosen of Vah.  Purrcy sacrificed her own adventuring in order to help lead Cronandan out of the bowels of Blackburrow... and promptly got lost on the way out of Southern Karana.<br>
<br>
The &quot;Once more into the Breach&quot; Award goes to - Cronandan of the League of Shadows.  Evil though he may be &lt;grumble grumble&gt; the man did the Tier'Dal proud, taking the storytelling aspect of the raid and running with it.  His chat channel descriptions of the carnage and destruction were masterful... I wish I had the foresight to have logged it.<br>
<br>
The &quot;Schoolboy Howler&quot; Award goes to - Me, sadly.  Even before the Raid started I managed to concoct a remarkably stupid way of dying.  While binding at the gypsy camp in Noth Karana, we were attacked by a Griffon.  Naturally, we led it over to the tower, where Guard Blakely could take care of it for us.  WEEEELLL, I decided to try and &quot;help&quot; the Guard by getting into the act as well (and if I could garner the XP and loot by sneaking in the last shot, that was a bonus).  Erp.  I was targetting the Guard.<br>
<br>
The &quot;Ding!&quot; Award goes to - Faettena of the Ledenyetz Troupe.  Part of the Lake Rathetear group, the spunky Halfling ranger reached the all-important 20th season milestone.  All hail, Faettena Hystrung!<br>
<br>
Special thanks as well to Grash, Losha, Daaxr, Rakash, Darai, Aadmer, and all of the others who participated in the event!<br>
<br>
Stay tuned for the next event... <br>
<br>
Uinin Stormsong<br>
